Prepare dataset:

I want to use the data \(x_t\) to predict \(y_{t+1}\). I merged cpi data and X, then add a new column y. y is the cpi value of next month, which is the value to be predicted. This assumes that the economic data of this month will affect the cpi data next month. The assumption is not very solid.

#Lag=1:
data_1=merge(cpi,X,by="month",all = T)
data_1=data_1 |> mutate(y=lead(CPI))

Dataset x contains 152 variables. These variables are highly correlated. The first method that occurs to me is dimension reduction. The PCA is a good method. I use data from all 168 observations to train the PCA model.

data_1=merge(cpi,X,by="month",all = T)
data_1=data_1 |> mutate(y=lead(CPI)) |> filter(is.na(y)==F)


#Train the PCA model
pca_data=data_1 |> select(!c("month","y","CPI"))
PCA=princomp(pca_data)

We can see that the first 8 dimensions can explain more than 95% of the variance. I assume that all other dimensions are noises and the first 8 components contain all the information I need. This assumption is not very solid either.

The data in x do not contain all the data I need to predict y. I assume that the conditional expectation \(E(y_{t+1}|X_t)\) is stable and other factors do not vary much in one year(12 months). For convenience, I use 12 months of data to train the regression and one month to do the testing(rolling windows).

\[ E(y_{t+1}|X_t) =\alpha+ PC_t \beta \quad t \in [i,i+12] \quad \\ y_{t+1} =\alpha+ PC_t \beta +\sigma \]

for any int \(i≥1\).

\(\beta\) is the coefficient matrix and \(\alpha\) is the intercept.

I choose Lasso Regression to do the prediction.

First, I use the data from 12 months to train the lasso regression to fit the parameter.

Then I calculate the PCs for next month and use Lasso Regression to predict inflation.

The code below is just for demonstration.

y_train=data_1[1:12,"y"]
y_test=data_1[13,"y"]
x_train=data_1[1:12,] |> select(!c("month","y","CPI"))
x_test=data_1[13,] |> select(!c("month","y","CPI"))


#collect 8 Principal Components and train the lasso regression.
PC=predict(PCA,newdata = x_train)[,1:8]

#Calculate scores for testing
PC_test=predict(PCA,newdata = x_test)[,1:8]

#Train the Lasso Regression: Find Lambda
cv_model <- cv.glmnet(PC, y_train, alpha = 1,nfolds = 3)
best_lambda <- cv_model$lambda.min

#display optimal lambda value
best_lambda
## [1] 0.3043395
#view coefficients of best model
pca_lasso <- glmnet(PC, y_train, alpha = 1, lambda =best_lambda)

I think the inflation of one month will affect the next month so I introduced an alternative model that added the CPI of the month into the Lasso regression.

data=data_1
dim=8

y_train=data[1:12,"y"]
y_test=data[13,"y"]
x_train=data[1:12,] |> select(!c("month","y","CPI"))
x_train_cpi=data[1:12,"CPI"] 
x_test=data[13,] |> select(!c("month","y","CPI"))
x_test_cpi=data[13,"CPI"]


#collect 8 Principal Components and train the lasso regression.
PC=predict(PCA,newdata = x_train)[,1:dim]
PCs=cbind(PC,x_train_cpi)

#Calculate scores for testing
PC_test=predict(PCA,newdata = x_test)[,1:dim]
PC_test2=append(PC_test,x_test_cpi)

#find lambda
cv_model <- cv.glmnet(PCs, y_train, alpha = 1,nfolds = 3)
best_lambda <- cv_model$lambda.min

#display optimal lambda value
best_lambda
## [1] 0.03446237
#view coefficients of best model

And then I did multiple tests of different parameters.

Lag=1 means I use \(X_t\) to predict \(y_{t+1}\). I also tried Lag=2 and Lag=3(a quarter) .

A more general model: \[ E(y_{t+Lag}|X_t) =\alpha+ PC_t \beta +CPI_t *\beta \quad t \in [i,i+window\ size] \quad \\ y_{t+Lag} =\alpha+ PC_t \beta + CPI_t * \beta +\sigma \]

I tried PCA with 8, 9, and 10 dimensions. Combining all these differences, I tested 18 models in total.

window size = 12 (one year)

Index1:6 represents different models. The best R-Square is around 0.83

green: dim = 8, red: dim = 9, blue: dim=10

Model1: Lag=1,no CPI

Model2: Lag=2,no CPI

Model3: Lag=3,no CPI

Model4: Lag=1,with CPI

Model5: Lag=2,with CPI

Model6: Lag=3,with CPI.

The model with CPI as an independent variable is better than without it.

Why do I add CPI as an independent variable in Lasso Regression but not in PCA?

The CPI of the former month is so important and if I put it in PCA with other 152 variables then it will dilute the weight of the variable. The results will be worse.

And then we found that the window length is too small(12 months) and we have more than 8 independent variables in Lasso. The Lasso estimation might not be very well. We tried different window lengths and we found that 12 months isn’t the best solution for the model. 60 months for training lasso is better.

Window size = 60 months.

We can see that after we add more samples into the Lasso, the difference between PCA dimensions becomes small. I think this is because as the sample size goes up, the Lasso regression can penalize the noises correctly and thus reduce the effect of noises.

Now we want to find the best window size. We knew that if the window size is too small, then the Lasso models won’t fit well. If the window size is too large, it will also lower the R-square.

We wrote another file that only try Lag=1, with CPI, dim=8 but different sample size. Here are the results:

See CPI_model6_find_window_size.R

The best model for CPI:

Lag=1, with CPI, dim = 8, window size = 60

Best R-Square = 0.9292863

The best model for PPI:

Lag=1, with CPI, dim = 8 window size = 84

The best R-Square: 0.9795128
